SIMPLE: stall
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stall
<hw>Stall</hw> <pr>(st⟦add⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stal</ets>, AS. <ets>steall</ets>, <ets>stall</ets>, a place, seat,
or station, a stable; akin to D. & OHG. <ets>stal</ets>, G. & Sw.
<ets>stall</ets>, Icel. <ets>stallr</ets>, Dan. <ets>stald</ets>,
originally, a standing place; akin also to G. <ets>stelle</ets> a place,
<ets>stellen</ets> to place, Gr. <grk>ste`llein</grk> to set, place,
send, and E. <ets>stand</ets>. ⟦root⟧163. See <er>Stand</er>, and cf.
<er>Apostle</er>, <er>Epistle</er>, <er>Forestall</er>,
<er>Install</er>, <er>Stale</er>, <pos>a.</pos> & <pos>v. i.</pos>, 1st
<er>Stalk</er>, <er>Stallion</er>, <er>Still</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A stand; a station; a fixed spot; hence, the stand or place where a
horse or an ox is kept and fed; the division of a stable, or the
compartment, for one horse, ox, or other animal.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In an oxes
<xex>stall</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stable; a place for cattle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At last he found a <qex>stall</qex> where oxen stood.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A small apartment or shed in which merchandise is
exposed for sale; <as>as, a butcher's <ex>stall</ex>; a
book<ex>stall</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A bench or table on which small articles of
merchandise are exposed for sale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How peddlers' <qex>stalls</qex> with glittering toys are laid.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A seat in the choir of a church, for one of the
officiating clergy. It is inclosed, either wholly or partially, at the
back and sides. The stalls are frequently very rich, with canopies and
elaborate carving.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dignified clergy, out of humility, have called their thrones
by the names of <qex>stalls</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Warburton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Loud the monks sang in their <qex>stalls</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>In the theater, a seat with arms or otherwise partly
inclosed, as distinguished from the benches, sofas, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The space left by excavation
between pillars. See <cref>Post and stall</cref>, under
<er>Post</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A covering or sheath, as of leather, horn, of iron,
for a finger or thumb; a cot; <as>as, a thumb <ex>stall</ex>; a finger
<ex>stall</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stall reader</b></col>, <cd>one who reads books at a
stall where they are exposed for sale.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cries the <qex>stall reader</qex>, ⟦ldquo⟧Bless us! what a word
on⟦br⟧
A titlepage is this!⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stall</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stall
<hw>Stall</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stalled</conjf> <pr>(st⟦add⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stalling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Sw. <ets>stalla</ets>, Dan.
<ets>stalde</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put into a stall or
stable; to keep in a stall or stalls; <as>as, to <ex>stall</ex> an
ox</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where King Latinus then his oxen <qex>stalled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fatten; <as>as, to <ex>stall</ex>
cattle</as>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To place in an office with the customary
formalities; to install.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To plunge into mire or snow so as not to be able to
get on; to set; to fix; <as>as, to <ex>stall</ex> a cart</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Burton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His horses had been <qex>stalled</qex> in the snow.</q>
<rj><qau>E. E. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To forestall; to anticipate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is not to be <qex>stall'd</qex> by my report.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To keep close; to keep secret.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stall</qex> this in your bosom.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stall</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stall
<hw>Stall</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>steallian</ets> to have
room. See <er>Stall</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To live
in, or as in, a stall; to dwell.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We could not <qex>stall</qex> together⟦br⟧
In the whole world.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To kennel, as dogs.</def>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be set, as in mire or snow; to stick
fast.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be tired of eating, as cattle.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stallage</ent>⟦br⟧
